question: explain back propagation, use the correct technical terms!
model_answer: backpropagation lowers the error of a mlp level by level recursively backwards. it back propagates an error from the last layer to the first layer by updating the weights. the updates are determined by the local gradient at each level which is computed by partial derivatives of the error and chain rule.
student_answer: the back propagation algorithm is a learning algorithm for updating in the weights in a multi-layer neural network. for updating the weights of all the layers, the error of each neuron must be calculated. in the back propagation algorithm, two phases will be defined:  - forward phase: the output of the neural network will be calculated and also the error of the neurons in the output layer.  - backward phase: the gradient of each neuron will be calculated, by using the calculated error on the output layer and the defined connections between the hidden layer and the output layer. if multiple hidden layers are defined, the error will be iteratively will be given backwards and the weights at each neuron will be updated.
student_answer_paraphrased: Back propagation algorithm to update the weight of a network of multiple layers. Each neuron's error must be calculated. question: define the mathematical model of a neuron, use the appropriate technical terms!
model_answer: mathematical model of a neuron consists of a set of synapses or connecting links where each link is characterized by a weight, an adder function (linear combiner), which computes the weighted sum (local field) of the inputs plus some bias and an activation function (squashing function) for limiting the amplitude of a neuron’s output.
student_answer: the neuron consists of synapses/connecting link each characterised by a weight. a linear combiner sums up the weighted sum of inputs to a local field. the local field is then passed through an activation function. the result of the activation function is the output.
student_answer_paraphrased: The neuron is composed of a synapse/connecting link (weight characterized) * A linear combiner sums up the input and local field (weight characterized) * The local field then passes through the activation function * The local function results in output.
model_answer_paraphrased: mathematical model of a neuron consists of a set of synapses or connecting links where each link is characterized by a weight, an adder function (linear combiner), which computes the weighted sum (local field) of the inputs plus some bias and an activation function (squashing function) for limiting the amplitude of a neuron’s output.
